Ethanol steam reforming (ESR) over CeO2 and Nb2O5-based supports was studied in order to determine the role played by the support in the processs of hydrogen generation for fuel cells. Temperature of calcination as well as the presence of dopants influence the chemical and physical characteristics of the supports with impact in the product mixture distribution. The CeO2 support calcined at 800 °C and the Nb2O5-Na support calcined at 500 °C presented the best results in ESR, both in terms of acidity, conversion and selectivity. While CeO2 gives predominantly hydrogen and acetone, Nb2O5 produces mores ethylene. In the two cases, however, conversion is low ( ∼ 15 %), so that the undesired products generated by the supports may not impact too much the product mixture under the presence of an active metallic phase. Density functional calculations (DFT) show that the preference for ethylene formation in Nb2O5 comes from the thermodynamic stability of the products, but not directly from acidic catalysis. Graphical abstract Keywords Ethanol Steam Reforming (ESR) Cerium Niobium Support Density Functional Theory (DFT) Data availability Data will be made available on request. 1 Introduction Supports constitute an essential part of catalysts for heterogeneous catalysis [1–6]. Even when the active phase is a metal (nano)particle, these tiny corpuscles are expected to be deposited over a support which is commonly a transition metal oxide. The properties of the support phase have a great impact on the overall performance of the catalyst [7,8]. Ethanol steam reforming (ESR) is a very important process in the search for alternative energy resources based on renewable materials [9–12]. Hydrogen is produced when a mixture of ethanol and water (and oxygen, in some cases) flow through a reactor filled with the solid catalyst. ESR normally uses supports as CeO2, Al2O3 and TiO2. Acidic supports can enhance ethanol conversion, but with the drawback of producing more ethylene by ethanol dehydration [6]. This leads to coke formation and catalyst deactivation. Among acidic supports, Al2O3 is probably the most popular one [13–16]. CeO2 is a basic support widely used in ESR [6,17]. It is known by its oxygen storage capacity [18,19] that grants storage and release of oxygen along a reaction more efficiently than other supports. This characteristic is pointed out as crucial for preventing coke formation and deactivation [8,20]. Nb2O5 is known as an acidic material [21–23], but it can be modified with the help of dopants. Nb2O5 is not commonly used for ESR, although our research group employed it effectively in some works on catalysis [24,25]. In a previous study, we have compared the performance of a Cu-Ni active phase deposited over supports of CeO2 and [25]. In the presence of N2 as an inert, the two supports presents comparable performances in the first 4 h of reaction in terms of conversion and selectivity to H2. However, CeO2 is more stable for longer reaction times. Although the active phase is expected to play the major role in hydrogen production, it is necessary to address the fact that most of the surface of a catalytic system for ESR is the support. The processes taking place directly over the support surface can also contribute to the final products distribution. In this way, it would be extremely helpful to determine which products to expect from a given support even before synthesizing the catalytic system. Metal-support interaction, of course, will also produce some effect. In most of the studies, the effect of the support is reported in combination with the active transition metal phase. In this way, identification of the exact contribution of the support to the products distribution can be difficult. In the present investigation, we are interesting in the properties of a series of isolated supports based on CeO2 and Nb2O5. CeO2 is a well established support for ESR and is taken here as a reference to evaluate the properties of the less known alternative Nb2O5. However, Nb2O5 is acidic, so that we doped it aiming at reducing its trend to produce ethylene and deactivate. Doping with CeO2 is an strategy followed in some works, with the best result obtained in the range 10%–12% of CeO2 [26,27]. Accordingly, we tested doping of Nb2O5 with 12% of CeO2. Alkali metal oxides can also be used to reduce acidity. Previous tests in our research group showed that doping Nb2O5 with just 0.1% of Na2O was enough to attain a substantial acidity reduction. In this way, we compared pure and doped Nb2O5 with the more popular CeO2 support. The main objective is to establish the role of the isolated supports on ESR in order to help in the choice of components of catalytic systems for ESR. 2 Methodology 2.1 Catalyst preparation Three supports of CeO2 were studied. The first one is just the commercial CeO2 used as provided. The second is CeO2 calcined at 550 °C in a muffle furnace, herein denoted . The third is CeO2 calcined at 800 °C, herein denoted . Three supports of Nb2O5 were also investigated. The first one is pure Nb2O5. The second is Nb2O5 doped with 0 . 1 % (m/m) of Na2O, herein denoted . The third is Nb2O5 doped with 12% (m/m) of CeO2, herein denoted . The Nb2O5 used in these supports was obtained from washing niobic acid with deionized water followed by calcination up to 500 °C for Nb2O5. Sodium nitrate and ammonium cerium nitrate were used for doping through wet impregnation. Calcination for formation was done at 500 °C, whereas for the temperature was 550 °C. 2.2 X-ray diffraction (XRD) XRD analyses were conducted using a Bruker D8 Advance diffractometer. The source of radiation was from Cu (CuK α , 0.20 °C/min for scan, 40 kV and 35 mA). All the diffractograms were interpreted using the database of the JCPD software from X’Pert HighScore from Philips. 2.3 Temperature programmed reduction (TPR) The analyses were done with 0.2 g of the catalyst in a quartz reactor with sintered bad and fed with a mixture of reductor gas containing 1.75% of H2 and 98.25% of Ar at a flow rate of 30 cm 3 /min. The heating rate was 10 °C/min, from ambient temperature up to 1000 °C. 2.4 Temperature programmed desorption (TPD) of NH3 and CO2 The analyses were conducted with 0.2 g of the sample within a quartz reactor with “U” shape in a Quantachrome Chembet-3000. Before the analyses, samples were submitted to a treatment with N2 over 1 h at 300 °C with gas flow of 20 cm 3 /min for drying and removal of adsorbed material. Samples were submitted to reduction with a mixture of H2/N2 (5% vol. H2) over 1 h with a heating rate of 10 °C/min from ambient temperature up to 500 °C, remaining at this temperature for additional 1 h. After this, adsorption of NH3 was conducted at 100 °C for 30 min with flow rate of 15 cm 3 /min of a mixture of NH3/N2 (5% vol. NH3). The system was purged for 2 h with N2 with a flow rate of 20 cm 3 /min, at 100 °C. Finally, NH3 was desorbed by keeping the N2 flux and heating the system up to 700 °C at a rate of 10 °C/min. The same procedures were adopted for CO2 desorption, but in this case adsorption and purge were conducted at 30 °C. 2.5 Themogravimetric analysis (TGA) and differential scanning calorimetry (DSC) The analyses were conducted with 0.02 g of the sample with air flux of 30 mL/min and heating rate of 10 °C/min, from ambient temperature up to 1000 °C in alumina sample containers. 2.6 Scanning electron microscopy (SEM) Micrographs were obtained with VEGA3 scanning electron microscope from Tescan. A secondary detector with HV tension of 20 kV was used. 2.7 Textural analysis from N2 adsorption–desorption isotherm Samples were impregnated and analyzed in a NOVA 1200 from Quantachrome by N2 adsorption and desorption at −196 °C. Before analyses, the samples were submitted to vacuum at 300 °C in situ. Volume and pore size were obtained by BET and BJH methods, for mesopores, and by Dubinin-Radushkevich (DR) for the microporous materials. 2.8 Catalytic tests Catalytic tests were conducted with in situ activation with a reductive atmosphere containing 60% of N2 and 40% of H2 (v/v), at a flow rate of 50 cm 3 /min and heated up to 500 °C (keeping this temperature thoughout the test). In all the tests, borosilicate glass was used to fill the reactor volume not occupied by the catalyst. The granulometry of the glass was the same of the catalysts and there were no sintering after reactions. N2 was used as carrier gas at a N2/ molar ratio of 2.5. The H2O/ molar ratio was kept at 10 and the volumetric spatial velocity was 70 dm 3 /(h ⋅ g c a t ). From mass transfer tests, the catalyst mass for the tests was chosen as 1.5 g with granulometry between 0.35 and 0.85 nm. 2.9 Density functional theory (DFT) calculation A 12-atoms cluster (Ce4O8) was used to model the catalytic properties of CeO2, while a 14-toms cluster (Nb4O10) was used for Nb2O5. In these clusters, we kept the same number of metal atoms, but this implies different number of oxygens. In order to find the most stable configuration, we used the Artificial Bee Colonny algorithm implemented in the ABCluster software [28,29] with the GFN1-xTB method [30]. The 10 most stable structures were further optimized using the B97-3c [31] density functional method with the Orca package [32]. The most stable structure was then selected for the reaction mechanism studies. Transition state structures were obtained using the NEB-CI method or direct optimimization to transition states. All the structures along the reaction paths were obtained with the B97-3c method. 3 Results and discussion 3.1 Characterizations 3.1.1 X-ray diffraction (XRD) Figs. 1 and 2 presents the XRD spectra for the CeO2 and Nb2O5-based supports, respectively. In Fig. 1, the characteristic peaks for CeO2 are essentially the same for all the samples in 2 θ = 28 . 5 ∘ , 33°, 47°, 56°, 59° and 69°. These results agree with previous works [17,33–36]. The crystal structure is of fluorite kind for all samples, as reported in previous works with CeO2 [37–42]. The peaks become more intense with increasing calcination temperature. Moreover, the 2 θ = 59° and 69° peaks became more evident. These observations indicates that calcination at higher temperatures makes the samples more crystalline, although the crystal structure continues to be of fluorite type, in agreement to other works reporting that thermal treatment does not affect the crystal structure of CeO2 [43]. Table 1 presents the crystallite size obtained from X-ray. For CeO2, the crystallite size for the uncalcined sample is smaller than those for the calcined samples. This suggests that calcination favors sintering, increasing the crystal size. For the Nb2O2-based supports, Fig. 2, the characteristic peaks are also common in 2 θ = 23°, 29°, 37°, 43°, 46°, 51°, 55°, 56°, 59°, 64° and 71° in accordance to other works with Nb2O5 [5,24,25]. The sample also presented CeO2 characteristic peaks at 2 θ = 29°, 33°, 48° and 56°. In 29° and 56° the peaks of Nb2O5 and CeO2 overlap each other. Another important aspect is that impregnation with ammonium cerium nitrate leads the peaks intensity to decreace. The thermogravimetric analysis (to be presented in the next sections) shows mass loss at about 800 °C which indicates that part of the ammonium cerium nitrate was not completely decomposed at 550 °C. Thus, the presence of this nitrate can reduce the crystallinity. Impregnation with Na2O, on the other hand, favored the intensity increase. According to Table 1, the particle sizes for the Nb2O5 samples are much larger than those observed for the CeO2-based supports. The particle size is unaffected by impregnation with Na2O, but it shows a substantial increase with CeO2 addition (from 45.7 to 54.9 nm). 3.1.2 Texture analysis Table 2 presents the texture analysis results, while Fig. S7 and S8 of Supplementary Material presents the adsorption–desorption profiles. For the three CeO2-based supports, the BET and t-plot external areas are the same, with the exception of CeO2, for which the two areas are not exactly equal but still very close. Therefore, these supports can be considered mesoporous. The increase in calcination temperature leads the BET area and the total pore volume to decrease while increasing the average pore diameter. Figs. S9 to S19 of Supplementary Material present the pore volume distributions. When the CeO2 supports are analyzed by the BJH method, we observe that the commercial sample calcined at 550 °C did not present a maximum, probably because the maximum falls bellow 20 Å. Calcination at 550 °C decreases the total pore volume. Calcination at 800 °C showed a different pore size distribution, with a maximum close to 50 Å and relatively large dispersion. In the case of the three Nb2O5-based supports, all are also mesoporous. The pore volume and pore diameter vary following the doping. The support presents lower BET area when compared to the other two. It must be noted that the Nb2O5 support was calcined only one time when formed from niobic acid. The other two supports were calcined a second time after impregnation. This second calcination may have caused the particle sintering and narrowing of pores, decreasing the area and pore volume and increasing pore diameter. The Nb2O5 support doped with CeO2 presented higher surface are relative to the undoped or the one doped with Na2O. The support presented higher BET area than Nb2O5. This characteristic of may have been somewhat transferred to , also calcined at 550 °C. Pore volume distribution for Nb2O5 presents a maximum close to 50 Å (Fig. S9 to S11), which indicates a mesoporous catalyst. The peak at a lower radius can indicate the presence of smaller pores, but still classified as mesopores. The presence of Na2O affects the pore distribution shifting the maximum to near 60 Å. Impregnation contributes to decrease pore volumes and calcination may have caused pore collapse, decreasing the cummulative pore volume and, hence, the specific area. With the collapse of the smaller pores, only the largest one remain. 3.1.3 Temperature programmed desorption of ammonia (NH3 -TPD) Table 3 presents the amounts of NH3 desorbed for all the studied supports, while Figs. S1 and S1 of Supplementary Material present the TPD profiles. The data allows us to measure the amount of acidic sites for each support. Given that the presence of acidic sites favors ethanol dehydration and ethylene generation, which is undesirable, we seek for a support with the lowest possible acidity. As a reference, we take the commercial, untreated, CeO2, with 0.350 mmol/g c a t of NH3 desorbed. When calcined at 550 °C, the amount of acidic sites increases (0.540 mmol/g c a t ). With a further increase in the calcination temperature, to 800 °C, we observe a substantial decrease in acidity (0.078 mmol/g c a t ). In other words, calcination of CeO2 for ethanol steam reforming might be done at temperatures in the vicinity of 800 °C, which is in accordance with the trend observed by Zaki et al. [44]. According to the XDR results, the crystal structure of the CeO2 supports does not change along the temperature range considered here. However, calcination can affect other structural characteristics like specific area and pore volume, according to the texture analysis results discussed above. The CeO2-800 support presents the lowest specific area. Therefore, it is expected that the amount of NH3 adsorbed will also decrease. It is noteworthy that the NH3-TPD profile for the commercial CeO2 (Fig. S1 of Supplementary Material) presents predominantly strong acid sites desorbed between 400 and 600 °C with a small contribution from a peak between 200 and 300 °C. The CeO2 support prepared by Seriyala et al. [45] presented weak acidic peaks near 77 °C (not captured in our analyzes) and also the strong acidic peak above 200 °C. However their analyzes were conducted only up to 400 °C and it was not possible to verify the existence of the strong acidic peaks present in our results above 400 °C. For the Nb2O5-based supports, the calcination temperature was 500 °C, except in the case of , which was calcined up to 550 °C. The pure Nb2O5 support presented acidity lower than the commercial CeO2 calcined at 550 °C. Doping with Na causes an expressive decrease in acidity (0.061 mmol/g c a t ) leading this support to be, in this fashion, more attractive than . As in the case of CeO2, the decrease in acidity for correlates with the decrease in specific area. 3.1.4 Temperature programmed desorption of CO2 ( ) Table 4 presents the results. CO2 desorption can be used to measure the basicity of the support. Higher values of desorbed CO2 means higher basicity. The general trend is similar to that for the acidity results in the sense the and presents the lower desorption values. Therefore, these two supports are both less acidic and less basic than the remaining ones. As the following sections will describe, these two supports also present the best results for H2 production ( for the CeO2-based and for the Nb2O5-based supports). Therefore, we can conclude that lower acidity and basicity are good for H2 production. 3.1.5 Themogravimetric analysis (TGA) and differential scanning calorimetry (DSC) Fig. 3 presents the TGA and DSC results for the CeO2-based supports. There is a considerable mass loss for the uncalcined sample (CeO2). This mass loss was significant up to 600 °C and presented peaks between 200 and 330 °C both in TGA and DSC. The sample calcined at 550 °C ( ) presented much less mass loss, up to 400 °C. Further increases in the calcination temperature ( ) reduces still more the mass loss, up to 200 °C. This indicates that the major part of the components responsible for the mass loss are oxidable at 550 °C. This reduction of mass loss with increasing temperature indicates the presence of interstitial water or functional groups in the surface of the commercial uncalcined CeO2. Fig. 4 presents the TGA an DSC results for the Nb2O5-based supports. None of the samples presented significant mass loss, since all were calcined at least at 500 °C. For , there is a small mass loss between 300 and 400 ° C . Since there is no equivalent mas loss for the TGA of the pure Nb2O5, it is obvious that this effect originates from the presence of NaNO3. According to the literature [46–48], this salt begins to decompose to NaNO2 at 600 ° C . However, it has been shown that the presence of Al2O3 nanoparticles accelerates the decomposition of NaNO3 [47]. Thus, it seems reasonable to interpret the mass loss between 300 and 400 °C as the NaNO3 decomposition to NaNO2 occurring at a lower temperature due to interaction with Nb2O5. The effect is small due to the also small amount of NaNO3 employed. The precursor and the support presented similar mass loss above 850 °C. The curves did not show mass loss due to . This can be explained by the decomposition of this substance along the drying process. Formation of CeO2, however, is confirmed by XRD. 3.1.6 Temperature programmed reduction (TPR) Table 5 presents the TPR results for the studied supports. All the CeO2-based supports presented 3 reduction peaks, which is a characteristic of this material [49,50]. However, the total percentage of reduction for each support varied considerably. The presence of interstitial water and other functional groups probably made the reduction difficult for the commercial material. After calcination at 550 °C, these contaminations were eliminated and about 60% of the material became Ce2O3. With calcination at 800 °C, the access to some pores was probably hinded, which led the percentage of oxide reduction to decrease. For the supports Nb2O5 and , the percentage of Nb2O5 reduction to NbO2 is practically the same and the temperature for the maximum is consistent with previous results [5]. The support presented 3 reduction peaks due to CeO2 in addition to the Nb2O5 reduction, which is another evidence of CeO2 formation in the support. For this purpose, we model the supports with the use of clusters containing 4 Nb or Ce atoms, Nb4O10 and Ce4O8. The first step was to determine the best cluster geometry. After the configurational search described in the computational details section, we arrived at the most stable structures which were used to optimized the intermediates and transition states of Figs. 10 and 11. The cluster structure itself changed little along the reactions. We optimized the cluster structure together with an ethanol molecule diposed at some arrangements and obtained the structure also displayed in Figs. 10 and 11 (first structure of Path 1) as the most stable for the ethanol-cluster complex. This complex was taken as the starting point for the reaction paths investigated. Fig. 12 presents the energy diagram for the two main reaction paths found. For the Nb2O5 cluster, two approaches were undertaken along the reaction path. In the first one, we kept all the reaction products, including H and OH groups, along the reaction steps. In the second approach, the additional H or OH groups generated by dissociation were removed prior the next reaction step. These two approaches represent two extreme cases in the reaction scenario. In one case, after a given reaction, the following step proceeds before the fragments generated have enough time to diffuse over the catalysts surface. In this way, these fragments can influence the kinetics and thermodynamics for the reactions. On the other extreme, after a given reaction, the fragments generated have enough time to diffuse over the catalyst surface prior the next step. In this case, fragments as H or OH generated along the reaction does not influence the relative energies. In the real system, we probably have a mixture of these two extremes, but with the predominance of one of them. According to our results, Fig. 12, the two extreme cases mentioned above produces different outcomes. When the H and OH fragments are kept along the reaction, ethylene is favored over acetaldehyde for Nb2O5 by thermodynamic reasons. When the cluster is cleaned after each step, the most stable product becomes acetaldehyde. In each case, the largest energy barrier occurs for the HO-C bond breaking along the reaction path 2. In this way, ethylene formation of not kinetically favored. Since experimentally ethylene is found in larger proportion than acetaldehyde, we probably have a situation more close to that in which the H and OH groups are somewhat in the neighborhood of the reaction sites. We also tested other possibilities for the first step of Path 2 in order to confirm that there would be no kinetic advantage for a variant of TS1b or an alternative path leading to ethylene. In TS1c, Fig. 10, we tested the possibility of Path 2 to be started by the C–H dissociation from the CH3 group. This transition state, however, has an activation energy of 98.24 kcal/mol, more than two times larger than that for TS1b (45.82 kca/mol). Next, we analyzed a possibility that involves a simultaneous C–O breaking from ethoxide and a C–H breaking, producing ethylene directly (TS2a-2). This was pointed out as an important process for ethanol decomposition over Al2O3 [2]. The activation energy for this transition state is 64.32 kcal/mol, which offers no advantage over the ones used to construct Fig. 12. Another possibility was the dissociation of the OH group assisted by a water molecule through hydrogen bonding (TS1b-2). The resulting activation energy was 49.93 kcal/mol, even high then the one without the water molecule. We also simulated the presence of a surface OH group that could assist the dehydration as proposed in Ref. [1], but the optimized structure leaves the OH group in the surface in an orientation unfavorable for any advantageous interaction. Finally, we tried to explicitly protonate the OH group to convert it in a good leaving group (H2O), but the proton is not stable over the ethanol OH. This proton is promptly transferred to one oxygen of Nb2O5, which suggests that the Nb2O5 oxygens are more basic than the ethanol OH. For CeO2 support, we were only able to calculate the reaction path without the presence of H or OH fragments due to severe convergence problems faced when these fragments were present. The reaction diagram actually predicts acetaldehyde as favored over ethylene. CeO2 is known by its oxygen mobility. Thus, OH groups generated along the reaction would probably be more easily eliminated or incorporated in the support structure so as to have a less important impact as in the case of Nb2O2. 4 Conclusions The studied supports showed quite sensible to calcination and doping. , as well as pure Nb2O5 (calcined at 500 °C), showed the highest acidities as determined by ammonia desorption experiments. On the other hand, and showed the smallest acidities. When submitted to catalytic tests, the two supports showed very distinct behaviors. The main product of the CeO2-based supports is hydrogen, with the best performance of . However, the hydrogen generated is related to acetone formation, so that acetone is inevitably present among the product mixture. Conversion is low. For the Nb2O5-based supports, the main product is ethylene generated from ethanol dehydratation. The ethylene produced promotes coke formation and catalyst deactivation. However, for , the conversion is quite low, so that the overall ethylene production can be considered acceptable. DFT calculations showed that the preference for ethylene over acetaldehyde in the Nb2O5 supports is related to the thermodynamics stability of the products, not by some kind of acid catalysis. coredata.dc:description: Ethanol steam reforming (ESR) over CeO2 and Nb2O5-based supports was studied in order to determine the role played by the support in the processs of hydrogen generation for fuel cells. Temperature of calcination as well as the presence of dopants influence the chemical and physical characteristics of the supports with impact in the product mixture distribution. The CeO2 support calcined at 800 °C and the Nb2O5-Na support calcined at 500 °C presented the best results in ESR, both in terms of acidity, conversion and selectivity. While CeO2 gives predominantly hydrogen and acetone, Nb2O5 produces mores ethylene. In the two cases, however, conversion is low ( ∼ 15 %), so that the undesired products generated by the supports may not impact too much the product mixture under the presence of an active metallic phase. Density functional calculations (DFT) show that the preference for ethylene formation in Nb2O5 comes from the thermodynamic stability of the products, but not directly from acidic catalysis.
